  "prompt": "Where does the pharmaceutical industry come up with the names for their drugs?",
  "response": "Drug naming is a complex process involving several strategies:\n\n1. Scientific Basis\n- Based on chemical structure or active ingredients\n- Derived from molecular composition\n- Using standardized pharmaceutical naming conventions\n\n2. Descriptive Names\n- Indicate drug's function or medical purpose\n- Suggest therapeutic effects\n- Highlight specific treatment areas\n\n3. Marketing Considerations\n- Memorable and easy to pronounce\n- Appealing sound and rhythm\n- Avoiding negative connotations\n- Distinctive from other drug names\n\n4. Regulatory Process\n- Must be approved by regulatory agencies like FDA\n- Checked to prevent potential confusion with other drug names\n- Must meet specific naming guidelines\n\n5. Professional Naming Firms\n- Many pharmaceutical companies hire specialized branding agencies\n- Professionals create names that are catchy, meaningful, and compliant\n\n6. Suffix/Prefix Conventions\n- Some drug classes use similar naming patterns\n- Example: Statins often end in \"-statin\"\n- Antibiotics might use \"-cillin\" or \"-mycin\"\n\n7. Latin or Greek Root Words\n- Often draw from medical terminology\n- Use language roots describing medical conditions or drug effects\n\nThe naming process is strategic, involving medical, linguistic, marketing, and regulatory considerations.",
